question:
Problem:
In the figure below, if the area of $\triangle ABC$ is 27, what is the value of $p$? [asy]
size(5cm);defaultpen(fontsize(9));
pair o = (0, 0); pair q = (0, 12); pair b = (12, 0);
pair a = (2, 12); pair t = (2, 0); pair c = (0, 9);

draw((-2, 0)--(15, 0), Arrow);
draw((0, -2)--(0, 15), Arrow);
draw(q--a--b);
//draw(a--t);
draw(a--c--b);

label("$Q(0, 12)$", q, W);
label("$A(2, 12)$", a, NE);
label("$B(12, 0)$", b, S);
label("$O(0, 0)$", o, SW);
label("$x$", (15, 0), E);
label("$y$", (0, 15), N);
//label("$T(2, 0)$", t, S + 0.6 * E);
label("$C(0, p)$", c, W);
[/asy]

generated_answer:
Solution:
Triangle $ABC$ is a right triangle, so we have $AB = \sqrt{12^2 + 10^2} = 2\sqrt{61}.$  Therefore, the area of triangle $ABC$ is
\[\frac{1}{2} \cdot 12 \cdot \frac{2\sqrt{61}}{2} = 6\sqrt{61}.\]Hence, we have $6\sqrt{61} = 27,$ so $\sqrt{61} = \frac{9}{2}.$

[asy]
size(5cm);defaultpen(fontsize(9));
pair o = (0, 0); pair q = (0, 12); pair b = (12, 0);
pair a = (2, 12); pair t = (2, 0); pair c = (0, 9);

draw((-2, 0)--(15, 0), Arrow);
draw((0, -2)--(0, 15), Arrow);
draw(q--a--b);
//draw(a--t);
draw(a--c--b);

label("$Q(0, 12)$", q, W);
label("$A(2, 12)$", a, NE);
label("$B(12, 0)$", b, S);
label("$O(0, 0)$", o, SW);
label("$x$", (15, 0), E);
label("$y$", (0, 15), N);
//label("$T(2, 0)$", t, S + 0.6 * E);
label("$C(0, p)$", c, W);
label("$10$", (q + a)/2, N);
label("$12$", (a + b)/2, E);
[/asy]

Finally, we have $p = \frac{27}{2\sqrt{61}} = \boxed{\frac{27}{4\sqrt{61}}}.$

