label("$A$", A, SW);
label("$B$", B, NW);
label("$C$", C, NE);
label("$D$", D, SE);
label("$P$", P, N);
label("$13\sqrt{3}$", B--C, E);
label("$12\sqrt{3}$", A--B, SW);
label("$x$", P--B, E);
label("$x$", P--A, W);
label("$h$", P--B, N);
[/asy]

Then
\[\frac{x}{2} = \sqrt{(x - 12\sqrt{3})^2 + h^2}.\]Also, the area of triangle $ABP$ is
\[\frac{1}{2} \cdot 12 \sqrt{3} \cdot 13 \sqrt{3} = 234.\]This area is also equal to $\frac{1}{2} \cdot x \cdot h,$ so $xh = 468.$  Then
\[x = \frac{468}{\sqrt{x^2 - 36}}.\]Squaring both sides, we get
\[x^2 = \frac{218592}{x^2 - 36}.\]Then $x^4 - 218592/x^2 - 36 = 0.$  This factors as
\[\left( x^2 - 468 \right)^2 = 0,\]so $x = 6 \sqrt{13}.$

Then
\[h = \sqrt{x^2 - 36} = 6 \sqrt{37},\]so the volume of the pyramid is
\[\frac{1}{3} \cdot \frac{1}{4} x^2 h = \frac{1}{3} \cdot \frac{1}{4} \cdot (6 \sqrt{13})^2 \cdot 6 \sqrt{37} = \boxed{702}.\]

Let $M$ be the midpoint of $\overline{AB}.$  Then $PM$ is perpendicular to plane $ABC,$ so $PM$ is the altitude from $P$ to $ABC.$  Also, $PM$ is the height of the pyramid.

From the Pythagorean theorem, $AM = 6 \sqrt{3}$ and $BM = 7 \sqrt{3}.$  Then $PM^2 = 7^2 - \left( \frac{13}{2} \right)^2 = \frac{15}{4}.$  Hence, $PM = \frac{\sqrt{15}}{2}.$

