label("$y=-x+18$",(9.5,8.5),W);
label("$y=\frac{1}{3}x+5$",(14.5,10.5),E);
fill((2,3)--(4,3)--(5,5)--(13,5)--(13,8)--(11,10)--(3,10)--(2,8)--cycle,gray(.7));
[/asy]

We can find the intersection points of the lines by solving the system of equations
\[\begin{aligned} y &= x - 2, \\ y &= -x + 18, \\ y &= \frac{1}{3}x + 5, \end{aligned}\]which gives $x = 4$ and $x = 13$. Therefore, the region $\mathcal{R}$ is the region bounded by the lines $y = x - 2$, $y = -x + 18$, and $y = \frac{1}{3}x + 5$ from $x = 4$ to $x = 13$.

