Now, consider a horizontal slice of the solid. Let $r$ be the distance from the slice to the line $3y-x=15$. Then the area of the slice is the difference between the areas of two disks with radii $r$ and $r+h$, where $h$ is the thickness of the slice. Therefore, the volume of the slice is
\[\pi((r+h)^2-r^2)h=\pi(2rh+h^2)h.\]
Since the slice is horizontal, we can express $r$ in terms of $y$ as $r=3y-15-x$. From $|8-x|+y\leq 10$ we get $x\leq 8-y+10$ and $x\geq y-8+10$. Combining these inequalities with $3y-x=15$, we obtain $3y-17\leq x\leq 3y-13$. Therefore,
\begin{align*}
r&=3y-15-x\\
&=3y-15-(3y-x)\\
&=x-2
\end{align*}
and
\begin{align*}
h&=\frac{dy}{dx}\cdot dx\\
&=\frac{dy}{dx}\cdot dy\cdot\frac{dx}{dy}\\
&=-\frac{1}{3}\cdot dy.
\end{align*}
Thus, the volume of the solid is
\begin{align*}
\int_4^8\pi(2(x-2)(-\tfrac{1}{3}dy)+(-\tfrac{1}{3}dy)^2) &=\pi\int_4^8(-\tfrac{2}{3}xy+\tfrac{2}{3}(x+y)-\tfrac{1}{9}y^2)dy\\
&=\pi\left[-\frac{xy^2}{3}+\frac{(x+y)y^2}{3}-\frac{y^3}{27}\right]_4^8\\
&=\pi\left(-\frac{256}{27}+\frac{448}{27}-\frac{512}{27}+\frac{256}{27}\right)\\
&=\frac{192\pi}{27\sqrt{2}}\\
&=\frac{64\pi}{3\sqrt{2}}.
\end{align*}
Thus, $m+n+p=\boxed{069}$.

The two inequalities define a quadrilateral.  We note that the line $|8-x|+y=10$ is the graph of two lines, namely $y=10-(8-x)=x+2$ and $y=10-|8-x|$.  The line $3y-x=15$ has slope $3$, so the line perpendicular to it through $(8,2)$ has slope $-\frac{1}{3}$.  Thus it has equation $y-2=-\frac{1}{3}(x-8)$.  This line intersects the lines $y=x+2$ and $y=10-|8-x|$ at $(6,8)$ and $(10,0)$, respectively.  The other two vertices of the quadrilateral are the intersections of $y=x+2$ with $3y-x=15$ and $y=10-|8-x|$ with $3y-x=15$.  These intersections are $(9,11)$ and $(7,3)$, respectively.  Thus the quadrilateral has vertices $(6,8)$, $(7,3)$, $(9,11)$, and $(10,0)$.

