We now revolve the region around the line $3y-x=15$.  This line has distance $\frac{15}{\sqrt{10}}$ from the origin, so the distance from the line to the point $(x,y)$ is $\frac{|3y-x-15|}{\sqrt{10}}$.  Thus the radius of the circle formed by revolving the point $(x,y)$ is $\frac{|3y-x-15|}{\sqrt{10}}$.  The volume of the solid of revolution is then
\begin{align*}
&\int_{6}^{7} \pi \left(\frac{|3y-x-15|}{\sqrt{10}}\right)^2 dy + \int_{7}^{9} \pi \left(\frac{|3y-x-15|}{\sqrt{10}}\right)^2 dy + \int_{9}^{10} \pi \left(\frac{|3y-x-15|}{\sqrt{10}}\right)^2 dy \\
&= \int_{6}^{7} \pi \left(\frac{3y-x-15}{\sqrt{10}}\right)^2 dy + \int_{7}^{9} \pi \left(\frac{x-3y+15}{\sqrt{10}}\right)^2 dy + \int_{9}^{10} \pi \left(\frac{x-3y+15}{\sqrt{10}}\right)^2 dy \\
&= \int_{6}^{7} \pi \frac{(3y-x-15)^2}{10} dy + \int_{7}^{9} \pi \frac{(x-3y+15)^2}{10} dy + \int_{9}^{10} \pi \frac{(x-3y+15)^2}{10} dy \\
&= \frac{\pi}{10} \left(\int_{6}^{7} (3y-x-15)^2 dy + \int_{7}^{9} (x-3y+15)^2 dy + \int_{9}^{10} (x-3y+15)^2 dy\right).
\end{align*}Evaluating each integral, we get
\begin{align*}
&\frac{\pi}{10} \left(\int_{6}^{7} (3y-x-15)^2 dy + \int_{7}^{9} (x-3y+15)^2 dy + \int_{9}^{10} (x-3y+15)^2 dy\right) \\
&= \frac{\pi}{10} \left(\frac{(x-19)^3 - (x-16)^3}{27} + \frac{(x-16)^3 - (x-22)^3}{27} + \frac{(x-22)^3 - (x-21)^3}{27}\right) \\
&= \frac{\pi}{270}(3x^3 - 150x^2 + 1737x - 4914).
\end{align*}Thus, $m+n+p = 3 + 270 + 4914 = \boxed{5187}$.

